{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657451/1924010401/0373.xml":{"full_text":"32\nLABOR RELIEF BILL\nLAID BEFORE HOUSE\nZihlman Would Have Public\nWork Done in Time of\nUnemployment.\nProviding: for the appointment of a\ncommission to investigate the needs\nof the nation for public works to be\ncarried on by federal, stale and mu\nnicipal agencies in periods of busi\nness depression and unemployment, a\nbill was introduced in the House to\nday by Representative Frederick N.\nZihlman of Maryland, chairman of the\nHouse committee on labor. This\nmeasure is Identical with one favor\nably reported by the Senate commit\ntee on education and labor and the\nHouse committee on labor in the\nSixty-seventh Congress.\nThe commission is called upon to\ndetermine where the public Interests\nwould be best served by the devel\nopment of public works. Including\nroads, aforestation and driliiage and\nirrigation of waste lands, and to se\ncure the co-operation of slate and\nmunicipal officials in the accomplish\nment of employment In. times of in\ndustrial depression and financial\npanics\nThe subject of unemployment has\nreceived the best- thought of states\nmen. psychologists and social work\ners since civilization began, and many\nplans have been proposed to'regulate\nthe Industrial cycles which occur\nevery five or seven years. There have\nalso been proposed plans for unem\nployment Insurance, which Is equiva\nlent to building up a reserve to lake\ncare of the unemployed and needy.\n\u201cI am of the opinion that this\nproblem can best be met by provid\ning that public works should be stim\nulated and pushed In times of depres\nsion,\u2019\u2019 said Representative Zihlman.\nIt is estimated that for every man\nemployed upon such public work as\nroad construction three others, men\nand women, are employed in making,\npreparing and transporting material\nand in the necessary clerical work\nincident thereto. Kvery mile of paved\nor concrete road requires many car\nloadS of freight and also the re\nvival of many industries, both di\nrectly connected with the work itself\nand stimulated by the purchasing\npower of the workers employed\nThe taking up of the slack in pe\nriods of business depression by stim\nulating public works has received\nthe Indorsement of some of the most\nnoted students, writers and publicists\nIn the country, and this bill, which\nis Intended to provide an agency\nwhich will ascertain necessary tacts,\nprepare practical and constructive\npiano and measures which will give\nCongress a working plan of action,\nwill do much to eliminate unemploy\nment and its relation to crime, de\nlinquency and prohibition.\nAIRCRAFT LEGISLATION\nPLANS BEING MADE\nAims Are Increased Efficiency and\nGovernment System of\nInspection.\nNew legislation designed to increase\nthe efficiency and use of commercial\naircraft Is being drafted by Chairman\nWinslow of the House committee on\ninterstate and foreign commerce and\nSecretary Hoover of the Department\nof Commerce, with the advice of\naviation experts.\nThe main purpose. Mr. Hoover said,\nis to establish a federal system of air\nplane inspection, which would give\nsome guarantee of security to the\npublic as to the safety of machines\nand appliances for passenger car\nriage, sport or exhibition.\nManufacturers of aircraft generally 1\nare anxious for such a federal policy,\nMr. Hoover added, pointing out that a\nbill brought forward by Senator\nAVadsworth, republican. New York, I\nfor a similar purpose passed the Sen- I\nate last year, but failed of enactment\nin the House.\nMANY SAVED BY U. S. AID.\nConditions in Greece Explained by\nRed Cross Report.\nAmerica's financial aid to the thou\nsands who fled into Greece from Turk\nish territory following the reverses\nof the Greek army in 1922 \u2018\u2018undoubt\nedly saved the Uves of large num- i\nbers who otherwise must have perish\ned,\u201d according to a report received\nyesterday by the Red Cross from the I\nAmerlcan-Athens relief committee, I\nomposed of prominent Americans In I\nGreece.\nThe report made special mention j\nof the fact that since that time the\nrefugees have \u201cdemonstrated almost 1\nunbelievable ability to assimilate]\nthemselves with the help of the Greek\ngovernment.\u201d\nOn\u00a9 of the most distinctive of all j\ncaverns Is the Ice Cave near Dobslna,\nin Hungary, which has an area of j\n10,000 square yards. Inside It Is al- i\nways winter, and. as the Ice takes j\nvery curious shapes, the effect Is\nstrikingly beautiful when the cave is\nIlluminated by electricity.\nBRYANT sal BOILER\ntkacOy suited to the\nBryant Boilers are built to one high\nstandard and in accordance with one\nproven principle.\nRegardless of size or the locality\nwhere installed, the results derived are\nuniformly satisfactory.\nWith twenty-six available sizes from\nwhich to select, there is positive assur\nance of obtaining a boiler exactly suited\nto any need encountered.\nf Learn of the exceptional results being\nS*r',.7TS* obtained with Bryant Boilers in Wash-\nington, Baltimore and throughout the\ncountry.\nFor Sale by Year Gas Company and by\nAlt Heating Contractors\nTHE BTffINT HEATER tMFG.OOt\nBaltimore Office I-ex ington Bldg.\nVANDALISM SUSPECTED.\nFiremen Find Broken Window\nWhere Blaze Wag Started.\nJames A. Gilbert, a night watch\nman, shortly after 3 o\u2019clock this\nmbrnlng discovered fire In a rear show\nwindow at the store of Schrott Broth\ners. dealers In novelties, 617 Houlslana\navenue northwest. Firemen said It\nwas due to Gilbert\u2019s prompt action\nthat a disastrous lire was prevented.\nDeputy Chief P, W. Nicholson re\nsponded, with two companies of fire\nmen, ami discovered a piece of glass\nhad been broken from the window\nnear where the fire started. Ho\nreached the conclusion that some per\nson hud reached through the opening\nutnd applied a match.\nThe fire started In heavy paste\nboard boxes of metal toys, the deputy\nchief stated, ami had not gained any\nheadway before It was discovered by\nthe night watchman. About eighteen\nmonths ago a disastrous fire occurred\nIn the store.\nDamage done by the fire this morn\ning was not more than SIOO, the\u2019chtef\nsaid. A further Investigation Is be\ning made to definitely determine the\norigin of the fire.\nHUGE COAST GUARD\nEUND PLAN WANES\nAdministration Considers\nAbandoning $2,000,000\nProgram for Building.\nAdministration officials are consid\nering abandonment of the proposal to\nexpend more than $30,000,000 in\nbuilding up the coast guard to com\nbat rum running and substituting use\nof naval cruisers, supplemented by\nthe advantages given under the pro\nposed twelve-mile liquor seizure\ntreaties with Great Britain and other\nnations.\nWhile no devision has been reached.\nPresident Coo\u2019idge has been urged by\nsome of h!s advisers to use naval craft\ntemporarily. New legislation might be\nnecessary.\nThe discussions so far have contem\nplated the use of cruisers only tem\nporarily. while the effectiveness of the\nliquor treaties was being ascertained\nand until the coast guard could be ex\ntended. if necessary, through moderate\nappropriations.\ngllllllilllllllllli\nU Automobile I\nBlue Book\nThere\u2019s always a best asS\nHH way. and the best way of =53\nS 3 motoring is to carry a Sg\nS 3 Blue Book in your car. sss\n=3 Then no matter where gg\n=3 you want to go, or how es;\n\u00a3=3 far it may be, you can\n=1 pick your route \u2014ac- S 5:\n=3 curately without having\n55 to depend upon road-side\nasa information, which is not \u00a3S\naaa always reliable. By con- SES\n|S stantly knowing where ESS\n=3 you are you will save E5\nJUS much time and wear both pa\n\u25a055 on your car and temper.\nThe National H\n|H Remembrance Shop g==\n(Mr. Foster's Shop)\nffj 14th St. On p\" oo v r vr. rom m\nAlso 122* I\u2019n. Are.\nMnnniiliinniiiiiiiiiiniiiiiiiHiiHfliiiiiS\nSewing Machine\nSpecials\nFor Saturday Only\n1 /-drawer Drophcad $00,50\nSinger, Satur